08210nam a22008295i 9780822387527DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20062006ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223875277 a10.1515/97808223875272doi  a(DE-B1597)552231  a(OCoLC)1224277899  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aF1234b.E15 2006 7aHIS0250002bisacsh04a306.09720904222204aThe Eagle and the Virgin :bNation and Cultural Revolution in Mexico, 1920–1940 /ced. by Mary Kay Vaughan, Stephen Lewis. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (395 p.) :b36 illustrations (20 in color)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tI. The Aesthetics of Nation Building -- tThe Noche Mexicana and the Exhibition of Popular Arts: TwoWays of Exalting Indianness -- tThe Sickle, the Serpent, and the Soil: History, Revolution, Nationhood, and Modernity in the Murals of Diego Rivera, José Clemente Orozco, and David Alfaro Siqueiros -- tPainting in the Shadow of the Big Three Frida Kahlo -- tMaría Izquierdo -- tThe Mexican Experience of Marion and Grace Greenwood -- tMestizaje and Musical Nationalism in Mexico -- tRevolution in the City Streets: Changing Nomenclature, Changing Form, and the Revision of Public Memory -- tII. Utopian Projects of the State -- tSaints, Sinners, and State Formation: Local Religion and Cultural Revolution in Mexico -- tNationalizing the Countryside: Schools and Rural Communities in the 1930s -- tThe Nation, Education, and the ‘‘Indian Problem’’ in Mexico, 1920–1940 -- tFor the Health of the Nation: Gender and the Cultural Politics of Social Hygiene in Revolutionary Mexico -- tIII. Mass Communications and Nation Building -- tRemapping Identities: Road Construction and Nation Building in Postrevolutionary Mexico -- tNational Imaginings on the Air: Radio in Mexico, 1920–1950 -- tScreening the Nation -- tIV. Social Constructions of Nation -- tAn Idea of Mexico: Catholics in the Revolution -- tGuadalajaranWomen and the Construction of National Identity -- t‘‘We Are All Mexicans Here’’:Workers, Patriotism, and Union Struggles in Monterrey -- tFinal Reflections WhatWas Mexico’s Cultural Revolution? -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen the fighting of the Mexican Revolution died down in 1920, the national government faced the daunting task of building a cohesive nation. It had to establish control over a disparate and needy population and prepare the country for global economic competition. As part of this effort, the government enlisted the energy of artists and intellectuals in cultivating a distinctly Mexican identity. It devised a project for the incorporation of indigenous peoples and oversaw a vast, innovative program in the arts. The Eagle and the Virgin examines the massive nation-building project Mexico undertook between 1920 and 1940.Contributors explore the nation-building efforts of the government, artists, entrepreneurs, and social movements; their contradictory, often conflicting intersection; and their inevitably transnational nature. Scholars of political and social history, communications, and art history describe the creation of national symbols, myths, histories, and heroes to inspire patriotism and transform workers and peasants into efficient, productive, gendered subjects. They analyze the aesthetics of nation building made visible in murals, music, and architecture; investigate state projects to promote health, anticlericalism, and education; and consider the role of mass communications, such as cinema and radio, and the impact of road building. They discuss how national identity was forged among social groups, specifically political Catholics, industrial workers, middle-class women, and indigenous communities. Most important, the volume weighs in on debates about the tension between the eagle (the modernizing secular state) and the Virgin of Guadalupe (the Catholic defense of faith and morality). It argues that despite bitter, violent conflict, the symbolic repertoire created to promote national identity and memory making eventually proved capacious enough to allow the eagle and the virgin to coexist peacefully.Contributors. Adrian Bantjes, Katherine Bliss, María Teresa Fernández, Joy Elizabeth Hayes, Joanne Hershfield, Stephen E. Lewis, Claudio Lomnitz, Rick A. López, Sarah M. Lowe, Jean Meyer, James Oles, Patrice Olsen, Desmond Rochfort, Michael Snodgrass, Mary Kay Vaughan, Marco Velázquez, Wendy Waters, Adriana Zavala  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aArt and statezMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 0aArtszMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 0aEthnicityzMexico. 0aIdentity (Psychology)zMexico. 0aNationalismzMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Mexico.2bisacsh1 aAceves, María, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBantjes, Adrian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBliss, Katherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHayes, Joy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHershfield, Joanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewis, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewis, Stephen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLomnitz, Claudio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLopez, Rick A.1 aLowe, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLópez, Rick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relato